When you have a method that returns a boolean and has a nullable `out` parameter, it is possible to add the nullable attribute `NotNullWhen` to the `out` parameter to specify the case where it won't be `null`, depending on the value of the boolean return type.

Would it make sense to have a `NotNullWhen` attribute for return values with different data types?

For example, let's say you have a method that returns an enum that describes the result of an operation, and only on one particular case (the "success" case), the `out` parameter will not be `null`:

```cs
enum OperationResult
{
    Success,
    ErrorA,
    ErrorB
}

OperationResult TryMethod([NotNullWhen(returnValue: OperationResult.Success)] out MyType? obj)
{
    obj = null;
    if (/* Error condition A*/)
    {
        return OperationResult.ErrorA;
    }
    else if (/* Error condition B*/)
    {
        return OperationResult.ErrorB;
    }
    obj = new MyType();
    return OperationResult.Success;
}
```

Since it could also be possible to have two or more enum values that are considered "success" cases, the `NotNullWhen` attribute could take an array of values:

```cs
enum OperationResult
{
    SuccessA,
    SuccessB,
    ErrorA,
    ErrorB
}


OperationResult TryMethod(
    [NotNullWhen(returnValue: new OperationResult[] { OperationResult.SuccessA, OperationResult.SuccessB} )]
    out MyType? obj)
{
    obj = null;
    if (/* Error condition A */)
    {
        return OperationResult.ErrorA;
    }
    else if (/* Error condition B */)
    {
        return OperationResult.ErrorB;
    }
    else if (/* Success condition A */)
    {
        obj = GetMyTypeForSuccessA();
        return OperationResult.SuccessA;
    }
    else // Success condition B
    {
        obj = GetMyTypeForSuccessB();
        return OperationResult.SuccessB;
    }
}
```

I just noticed something really weird.

I maintain a [library](https://github.com/thomaslevesque/Linq.Extras) that provides extension methods to `IEnumerable<T>`. This library exposes a `ToHashSet` method. Everything worked fine, until `Enumerable.ToHashSet` was also introduced in `net472`, `netcoreapp2.0` and `netstandard2.1`. Predictably, this caused an ambiguous invocation error when both the Linq.Extras and System.Linq namespaces were imported. So far so good, it makes sense.

I set out to fix the issue in my library by adding additional targets without the `ToHashSet` method, but then I realized something strange: I should have encountered the problem in my tests, but I didn't. My tests target multiple TFMs, including `netcoreapp2.0`, and look roughly like this:

```csharp
using System.Linq;

namespace Linq.Extras.Tests
{
    public class MyTests
    {
        [Fact]
        public void Test1()
        {
            IEnumerable<string> enumerable = new[]{ "hello", "world", "HELLO" };
            var result = enumerable.ToHashSet(StringComparer.OrdinalIgnoreCase);
            ...
        }
    }
}
```
Notice that in this test, both `System.Linq.Enumerable.ToHashSet` and `Linq.Extras.XEnumerable.ToHashSet` are in scope. So I should get an ambiguous invocation error... But I don't! It always uses `Linq.Extras.XEnumerable.ToHashSet`.

The only reason I can think of is that the test namespace (`Linq.Extras.Tests`) is "under" the namespace the contains the extension method (`Linq.Extras`). And indeed, if I change the test namespace to `Foo` and add a `using Linq.Extras`, I get the expected error.

So, is this behavior expected? Is there an overload resolution rule that prioritizes extension methods in a parent namespace? Where is this rule mentioned?

